04233nam a22005055i 9780773568358DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20002000xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735683587 a10.1515/97807735683582doi  a(DE-B1597)656782  a(OCoLC)180704380  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aPS8513.A593bZ62 2000eb 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a813/.541 aClement, Lesley D., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aLearning to Look :bA Visual Response to Mavis Gallant's Fiction /cLesley D. Clement. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2000] 4cÂ©2000  a1 online resource (304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tPreface and Acknowledgments -- tAcquiring a Sense of Perspective: The Early Years -- tInside and Outside the Frame: Characters in Search of an Audience (1959-1964) -- tTyranny of Form: Adjusting Proportions in the Stories of the Early 1960s -- tPortraiture and Landscapes of "Life at Point Zero": A Decade of Remembering and Exorcizing and Remembering (1963-1972) -- tColoration of Monochromatic Moments (1968-1978) -- tMapping Panoramic Landscapes: Idyll, Farce, Parody -- tTowards an Illumination of Gallant's Late Fiction -- tNotes -- tWorks Cited -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Learning to Look Lesley Clement traces the evolution of Mavis Gallant's visually evocative style through five decades of her short fictional works. From her earliest explorations of displacement and the disparity between perception and reality, through her later explorations of memory and history, to her more recent explorations of the role of culture in a contemporary world where commercialism and madness threaten to extinguish the potential for illumination and enlightenment, Gallant envisages and renders her fictional world with the techniques analogous to those of visual artists.Clement shows us that Gallant's fiction of the 1940s and 1950s exhibits a keen interest in perspective and proportion achieved through concentration on line, that her fiction of the 1960s and early 1970s reveals a heightened interest in composition achieved through a focus on framing, proportion, and form or shape, and that her fiction after the mid 1970s demonstrates the full realization of her art through attention to colour and light. Gallant increasingly explores the boundaries between visible and invisible worlds as the lines, shapes, and colours suggested by her allusions, analogies, and structures give her fiction the perspective, proportion, density, and fluidity that illuminate the printed page and challenge us as readers. Alert to visual cues in Gallant's fiction we acquire a heightened perception of the manifold richness of worlds and lives that might otherwise have been relegated to the unseen and unsung.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356835840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773568358423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773568358/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles